\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:lower-semi"

\end_inset

A function 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle f:X\subseteq\R^{n}\to\R}$
\end_inset

 is called lower semi-continuous at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

 if for every real 
\begin_inset Formula $y<f(x_{0})$
\end_inset

 there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)>y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is lower semi-continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 iff 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle \liminf_{x\to x_{0}}f(x)\geq f(x_{0})}.
\]

\end_inset

The function is lower semi-continuous if is it so at every point in its
 domain.
 The definition of upper semi-continuous is analogous with the inequalities
 reversed and 
\begin_inset Formula $\liminf$
\end_inset

 replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\limsup$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

